VALUES
(43, 4, 1, 43, 3, 26, 26, 'baptized more disciples than John', 'Baptism and Discipleship Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the act of baptism and the growing number of disciples. John 3:26 mentions Jesus baptizing and attracting followers, which leads to the Pharisees'' awareness in John 4:1.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 1, 47, 4, 5, 5, NULL, 'Servanthood in Ministry', 'This connection highlights the theme of servanthood in ministry. In John 4:1, Jesus'' growing influence leads to more disciples, while 2 Corinthians 4:5 emphasizes preaching Christ and serving others for His sake.', 'theme', 0.349, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 1, 44, 10, 36, 36, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus'' Authority', 'This connection highlights the authority of Jesus as Lord, which is implied in both passages. In John 4:1, Jesus is gaining disciples, indicating His growing influence, while Acts 10:36 explicitly states His lordship over all.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 1, 46, 2, 8, 8, 'the Lord knew', 'Knowledge and Misunderstanding of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of knowledge regarding Jesus'' identity. In both passages, the lack of understanding by the Pharisees and the ''princes of this world'' leads to significant consequences regarding Jesus'' ministry and crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 1, 46, 15, 47, 47, NULL, 'Earthly vs. Heavenly Contrast', 'This connection highlights the contrast between Jesus, who is described as the ''Lord from heaven,'' and the earthly nature of humanity. The mention of Jesus baptizing more disciples than John in John 4:1 sets the stage for understanding His divine authority as the second man.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 1, 42, 1, 76, 76, 'more disciples than John', 'Preparation for the Lord''s Work', 'This connection highlights the role of Jesus in making disciples, which aligns with the prophetic mission of preparing the way for the Lord mentioned in Luke. Both passages emphasize the importance of preparing for the Lord''s coming and the growth of His ministry.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 1, 59, 2, 1, 1, NULL, 'Faith and Discipleship Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of faith in Jesus as it relates to the community of believers. Both passages emphasize the importance of not showing favoritism, suggesting that true discipleship involves equality among followers of Christ.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 2, 44, 10, 48, 48, NULL, 'Baptism in Early Ministry', 'This connection highlights the act of baptism as a significant practice in both passages. In John 4:2, the disciples are involved in baptism, while Acts 10:48 emphasizes the command to baptize in the name of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 2, 46, 1, 13, 17, 'Jesus himself baptized not', 'Baptism and Preaching Emphasis', 'Both passages emphasize the distinction between baptism and the preaching of the gospel. John 4:2 notes that Jesus himself did not baptize, while 1 Corinthians 1:17 states that Paul was sent not to baptize but to preach.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 3, 40, 10, 23, 23, 'departed again into Galilee', 'Journey and Persecution Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of movement in response to persecution. In both passages, the act of leaving one place for another signifies a response to challenges faced in ministry.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 3, 43, 3, 22, 22, 'departed again into Galilee', 'Journey from Judea to Galilee', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' movement between Judea and Galilee. In John 3:22, Jesus is in Judea, while John 4:3 indicates his departure from there to Galilee.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 3, 43, 10, 40, 40, 'departed again into Galilee', 'Journey of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' movement from one region to another, highlighting his travels. The transition from Judea to Galilee in John 4:3 connects to his later journey beyond Jordan in John 10:40.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 3, 43, 11, 54, 54, 'departed again into Galilee', 'Jesus'' Movement and Secrecy', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' movement away from public view. In John 4:3, he departs to Galilee, while in John 11:54, he retreats to Ephraim, indicating a pattern of seeking solitude.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 3, 41, 3, 7, 7, 'departed again into Galilee', 'Jesus'' Movement Between Regions', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' movement from Judea to Galilee, as noted in both passages. John 4:3 mentions Jesus departing into Galilee, while Mark 3:7 references a multitude from Galilee and Judea following him.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 3, 43, 1, 43, 43, 'into Galilee', 'Jesus'' Movement to Galilee', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' journey to Galilee in both passages. In John 4:3, He departs to Galilee, while in John 1:43, He actively seeks out Philip in Galilee.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 4, 42, 17, 11, 11, 'must needs go through Samaria', 'Journey Through Samaria', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of traveling through Samaria. This connection highlights the significance of Samaria in Jesus'' journey as he moves towards Jerusalem.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 4, 42, 9, 51, 52, 'must needs go through Samaria', 'Journey Through Samaria', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' intentional journey through Samaria in both passages. In John 4:4, he ''must needs go through Samaria,'' while in Luke 9:51-52, he sends messengers to a Samaritan village, indicating a purposeful engagement with Samaritans.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 4, 40, 10, 5, 6, 'must needs go through Samaria', 'Jesus'' Mission and Samaria', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' journey through Samaria in John 4:4, contrasting with the directive in Matthew 10:5-6 to avoid Samaritans. Both passages emphasize the significance of Samaria in Jesus'' ministry and the initial focus on Israel.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 4, 42, 2, 49, 49, 'must needs go', 'Divine Purpose and Mission', 'This connection highlights the theme of necessity in fulfilling divine purpose. Both passages emphasize a sense of obligation to pursue God''s will, as seen in ''must needs go'' and ''I must be about''.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 5, 6, 24, 32, 32, 'parcel of ground that Jacob gave to his son Joseph', 'Connection of Joseph''s Burial Site', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the parcel of ground that Jacob gave to Joseph. John 4:5 mentions Sychar, which is near Shechem, where Joseph''s bones were buried as noted in Joshua 24:32.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 5, 1, 33, 19, 19, 'parcel of ground that Jacob gave', 'Connection of Sychar and Shechem', 'This connection highlights the geographical significance of Sychar, which is near the land associated with Jacob''s purchase of a field from Hamor, Shechem''s father. Both passages reference important locations tied to Jacob and his descendants.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 5, 1, 48, 22, 22, 'the parcel of ground that Jacob gave to his son Joseph', 'Connection of Land and Heritage', 'This connection highlights the significance of land given to Joseph, as mentioned in both passages. John 4:5 references the city of Sychar, linked to the parcel of ground Jacob gave to Joseph, while Genesis 48:22 speaks of a portion given to Joseph above his brethren.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 5, 43, 4, 12, 12, 'Jacob gave to his son Joseph', 'Connection Between Jacob and the Well', 'Both passages emphasize Jacob''s significance in relation to the well. The first mentions Jacob giving the land, while the second references the well he provided for his descendants.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 6, 58, 4, 15, 15, 'being wearied with his journey', 'Human Experience of Jesus', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' weariness in John 4:6 and His empathy in Hebrews 4:15. Both passages emphasize His shared human experience and ability to relate to our struggles.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 6, 58, 2, 17, 17, 'being wearied with his journey', 'Connection of Weariness and Humanity', 'This connection highlights the shared theme of Jesus'' humanity. In John 4:6, Jesus experiences physical weariness, while Hebrews 2:17 emphasizes his identification with humanity to serve as a high priest.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 6, 40, 8, 24, 24, 'wearied with his journey', 'Weariness and Rest', 'This connection highlights the theme of weariness and rest in both passages. Jesus is described as being ''wearied'' at the well and ''asleep'' during the tempest, emphasizing his human experience of fatigue.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 6, 40, 4, 2, 2, 'being wearied with his journey', 'Connection of Weariness and Hunger', 'This connection highlights the physical needs of Jesus in both passages. In John 4:6, Jesus is wearied from his journey, while in Matthew 4:2, he experiences hunger after fasting. Both instances emphasize the human experience of fatigue and need.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 6, 42, 2, 7, 7, 'wearied with his journey', 'Connection of Weariness and Humility', 'This connection highlights the themes of weariness and humility in both passages. Jesus, weary from his journey, sits at a well, while Mary lays her child in a manger due to lack of space, emphasizing humble circumstances.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 6, 42, 9, 58, 58, 'being wearied with his journey', 'Jesus'' Weariness and Lack of Rest', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' physical exhaustion in John 4:6, where He is described as wearied. Similarly, in Luke 9:58, Jesus notes His lack of a place to rest, emphasizing His transient lifestyle and the sacrifices He made during His ministry.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 6, 43, 11, 9, 9, 'about the sixth hour', 'Connection of Time and Light', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of time, with John 4:6 noting the specific hour and John 11:9 discussing the hours in the day. This connection highlights the significance of timing in Jesus'' ministry and the metaphorical use of light.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
